AGI - The ambassadors of the Twenty-seven > reached 'a principle agreement' on the use of profits generated by Russian assets > immobilized in the European Union. The funds - deriving from the immobilization and net of the taxation - will be destined to the fund for the Ukrainian resumption (10%)> and the supply of weapons (90%)>. The agreement, which has yet to be confirmed at the Union's ministers level, comes after long and harsh debates on how to use Russian state assets blocked after the invasion of Ukraine. A treasure of approximately 210 billion euros.
&nbsp;
The European Commission had presented in March a plan to confiscate the proceeds produced by these goods, which could allow to free between 2.5 and 3 billion euros a year in favour of Kiev. Several states - but also the ECB - have not hidden the fear that such an initiative can have legal repercussions and especially in financial markets', affecting the credibility of the EU in the eyes of foreign investors. In recent months Moscow has not failed to threaten legal actions "for decades" in the case of the use of extra profits of its immobilized assets.
&nbsp;
The vast majority of immobilized Russian assets are located in Belgium. They are administered by Euroclear, an international fund deposit company. Last year the group managed to obtain revenue for a total of 4.4 billion euros, a sum taxed by the Belgian State as tax on companies for a value that in 2024 should amount to 1.7 billion. In the agreement reached between the Twentyssettes the percentage - from 3 to 0.3% of net profits - which should be allocated to Euroclear for fund management operations.&nbsp;

