Benjamin Netanyahu>, the Israeli prime minister who is under pressure from the United States and other allies to accept a truce, said that while sending negotiators to the talks, “in tandem, we continue to lead the war against Hamas”. Analysts said that Israel's incursion to Rafah could increase pressure on Palestinian militants but that results can be opposed. That is, is it an action that will lead to an agreement or sabotage the ongoing talks?. The move does not seem to represent the full invasion of Rafah's land that Israel threatened for a long time and on which many of its allies wanted it to be avoided. The Israeli army defined the move “a very precise anti-terrorism operation >”.&nbsp;Netanyahu is trying to reassure its numerous internal, military and diplomatic critics. &nbsp;&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The director of a Rafah hospital said that from the beginning of the raid 27 lifeless bodies and 150 wounded were brought into its structure. Tel Aviv's troops claimed to have killed about 20 people in Rafah, describing the dead as Hamas.&nbsp militants;
Many international officials and observers have condemned the incursion. The Egyptian Ministry of Foreign Affairs has defined the seizure of the Rafah Pass by Israel a “dangerous escalation”, while Josep Borrell, > the highest diplomat of the European Union, has declared to fear that it can cause “many victims”.
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
