AGI - The floods of the last days in southern Brazil, which caused at least 96 deaths and 131 missing, affected about 80 indigenous communities and forced 466 indigenous families to abandon their villages or their reserves.&nbsp;According to the National Indio Foundation (Funai), 1.846 indigenous families were directly affected by floods and 5,415 indirectly, mainly by groups and indigenous families. At least 47 villages, 14 lands and a reserve of these last two peoples were involved by the largest natural catastrophe in the history of Rio Grande do Sul, a state to the extreme south of Brazil bordering Argentina and Uruguay.
&nbsp;
In addition to the 466 families forced to leave their communities to escape floods, 148 others are isolated in the Indigenous Land Rio da Várzea>, within the jurisdiction of the municipality of Liberato Salzano, due to the destruction of the only access roads.
The organization Articulação dos Pueblos Indígenas da Região Sul> has published on its website a map with the location of villages hit by rains since last Thursday. Other populations affected by the weather disaster are the Guaraní Mbya and Xokleng, whose communities are distributed in 49 different municipalities. The most affected are located in the metropolitan area of Porto Alegre, the capital of Rio Grande do Sul, where many neighborhoods were flooded by the rising of the Guaiba River.
&nbsp;
According to the organization, the indigenous populations affected need mattresses, blankets, tarpaulins and, above all, food and drinking water. Marcos Kaingang>, sent by the Ministry of Indigenous Peoples in Rio Grande do Sul to guide the work of support for affected ethnic groups, said that the main concern is for the communities left isolated and for families sheltered within churches, schools and gyms. “Our role is to look for the means and support that is most needed, as food baskets, the first request of these families, as well as medicines and personal hygiene articles,” said Kaingang in a Ministry statement. He added that the agency is working to ensure that indigenous peoples are included in humanitarian assistance campaigns without the risk of being forgotten.
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> Catastrophe and aid
The drama of the flood has worsened in Porto Alegre and hundreds of other cities in southern Brazil, where humanitarian aid is beginning to arrive between the lack of drinking water and new warnings of storms in the coming days. This explains the analysts and the local Civil Protection, the &nbsp; weather catastrophe in the history of the Region. “The figures continue to rise and unfortunately we expect that they are still very imprecise because the emergency is still in progress >”, declared the governor of the Eduardo Leite> state announcing the allocation of 200 million reais (about 40 million dollars) to cope with the most immediate criticalities. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
In more than 400 affected municipalities, including Porto Alegre, nearly 160,000 people were evacuated from their homes due to floods caused by flooding of rivers after heavy rain. The shipments of aid and donations from all over the country began to arrive on Tuesday where “the most urgent request is that of water”, said Sabrina Ribas, spokesman for Civil Protection >, in a press conference. “I’m at the limit. God does not want to remain without water," said AFP Elizabeth, a 67-year-old woman who did not reveal her last name, while she loaded buckets in one of the taps available in Alvorada, a city near Porto Alegre.
Only two of the six water treatment plants are in operation, said the office of the mayor of the state capital, who ordered the ration. &nbsp;&nbsp; In a series of operations “similar to those that apply during a war”, the Brazilian Navy will send to Rio Grande do Sul its “Atlantic” ship, the largest in Latin America, with two mobile water treatment stations.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
In a district of Canoas, in the metropolitan area of Porto Alegre, the boats go back and forth to save those who decided to stay in their homes until the last minute, or who still did not manage to evacuate. A group of neighbors repair themselves under a canopy of luck. Standing next to a large pot of food, Altamir Postal explains that all food comes from donations: “Whoever needs it comes and eats it.” According to accounting officer 51, the water level has retired from Monday, but a few meters away the stagnant water smell reminds us that the tragedy is not over. In the region, about 15,000 military, firefighters, police and volunteers are working to save people in difficulty > using aircraft, boats and vehicles of all kinds.
&nbsp;
The logistics for the distribution of water and food is incessant, with " helicopters that go and come to assist above all the more distracted and subject to collapses", while trying to free the roads, said Ribas, of the Civil Protection. President Luiz Inácio Lula de Silva> said that “the emergency funds will begin to be granted” for “the first aids”. And although “the extent of devastation” is not yet “note”, he reiterated that “the resources will not fail to meet the needs” of the state. Moreover, if the rains will delay the crops in this agricultural region, “we will import rice and beans” in the country to avoid an increase in prices, he warned.
&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> The latest forecasts
The situation could worsen: the National Institute of Meteorology (Inmet) > warned of "very dangerous" storms in the south of the state until the evening of today, Wednesday, May 8, with heavy rains, winds and perhaps hail. In addition to the low temperatures, there are rainfall in the centre and north of the territory, which could increase on Friday and Saturday and “damaging rescue operations”, said the meteorologa Catia Valente. The river Guaíba>, which crossed over Porto Alegre, remained at the historic level of 5.28 meters reached Tuesday. The structures of five dams are “at risk of breaking”, declared the government. Satellite images showed that “the flood changed the map of the metropolitan region” of Porto Alegre, said the specialized website MetSul.<br> &nbsp;
